  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over the past few decades:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970, USA)\n- First international efforts to track financial crimes\n- Limited regulatory frameworks\n\n2. Key Milestones\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Introduced global anti-money laundering standards\n- Recommended comprehensive legal frameworks\n\n3. Major Legislative Developments\n- EU Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Patriot Act (2001, USA)\n- Increased reporting requirements\n- Enhanced customer due diligence\n- Stricter penalties for non-compliance\n\n4. Modern Approaches\n- Digital transaction monitoring\n- Cryptocurrency regulation\n- Enhanced international cooperation\n- Risk-based compliance strategies\n- Advanced technological tracking mechanisms\n\n5. Recent Trends\n- Expanded beneficial ownership transparency\n- Stricter regulations for virtual assets\n- More comprehensive cross-border information sharing\n- Greater emphasis on preventing terrorist financing\n\n6. Technological Integration\n- Machine learning detection systems\n- Real-time transaction screening\n- Advanced data analytics\n- Automated compliance checks\n\nThe legislation continues to evolve, becoming more sophisticated and technologically integrated to address emerging financial crime challenges.",
